<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-inner">
    <div class="badge"><span class="badge-dot"></span>From rough to ready</div>
    <h1 class="hero-h">Turn Word reports and tables into <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">polished output.</em></h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">The work is done. The report exists. What eats your afternoon is making it presentable: reformatting, building the summary, cleaning the table, cutting it down for the people who will not read ten pages. Claude does that part. You upload the rough material, describe the output you want, and download a finished document. No manual reformatting.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">The short answer</span>
    <h2 class="h2">How it works, start to finish</h2>
    <p class="body answer">Upload your draft, report, notes, or table into Claude, then tell it the output you need: a clean Word document with headings and a summary, a tidy table, an executive summary, or a slide outline. Claude restructures and formats the material and, using its document Skills, can hand you a finished file to download. Your job shifts from reformatting to reviewing. You confirm the substance is right and send it. The grunt work disappears.</p>
    <p class="body">The key shift in thinking: stop treating Claude as a place to chat and start treating it as the step between "the content exists" and "it is ready to send."</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">The workflows</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Five rough-to-ready jobs</h2>

    <h3 class="h3">1. Reformat a messy report into a clean document</h3>
    <p class="body">You have the content, but it is a wall of inconsistent headings and stray bullet points. Upload it and ask for structure.</p>
    <div class="prompt"><span class="plabel">Try this</span>"Take this draft and produce a clean Word report: a short executive summary at the top, consistent headings, tightened prose, and a contents list. Keep all the facts and figures exactly as they are. Give me the file to download."</div>

    <h3 class="h3">2. Turn a raw table into something readable</h3>
    <p class="body">A dense table that nobody can parse becomes a clear one with a takeaway. Paste or upload it and ask Claude to clean the formatting, sort it sensibly, and add a one-paragraph "what this shows" above it. Always check the numbers yourself before it goes out.</p>

    <h3 class="h3">3. Compress a long report into an executive summary</h3>
    <p class="body">Leadership will not read the full thing. Upload the report and ask for a one-page summary written for a busy executive: the decision, the three things that matter, and the recommended next step. For board-level work, pair this with <a href="/how-to-write-board-decks-with-claude">how to write board decks with Claude</a>.</p>

    <h3 class="h3">4. Convert a document into a presentation</h3>
    <p class="body">Hand Claude the report and ask for a slide deck.</p>
    <div class="prompt"><span class="plabel">Try this</span>"Turn this report into a 10-slide deck for a leadership audience. One clear idea per slide, a strong opening and closing, and speaker notes. Build the deck file so I can download it."</div>
    <p class="body">You still shape the emphasis and the story. Claude removes the hours of restructuring.</p>

    <h3 class="h3">5. Standardize formatting across documents</h3>
    <p class="body">If your team's documents all look different, give Claude your template or a description of your house format and have it apply that standard to whatever you upload. This is where teams get consistency without a style police. The patterns live in <a href="/claude-prompts-for-operations">Claude prompts for operations</a>.</p>

    <div class="notice"><strong>How the finished files happen:</strong> producing a properly formatted Word doc, deck, or spreadsheet uses Claude's document Skills, the packaged expertise that knows how these files should be built. You do not manage any of that. You ask for the format and download the result. More on this in <a href="/claude-artifacts-skills-connectors-explained">Artifacts, Skills, and Connectors explained</a>.</div>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">Do it well</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Two habits that make the output great</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>Give it your standard once.</strong> Keep a template and a short note on your house format in a Project. Then every document you produce comes out consistent, and you never re-explain what "polished" means to you.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Review the substance, not the format.</strong> Claude reliably handles structure and presentation. You own the judgment: are the numbers right, is the emphasis correct, does the recommendation hold. That division of labor is the whole win, and learning to trust it is a core part of <a href="/claude-fluency">Claude Fluency</a>. If you are still finding your feet, start with <a href="/claude-for-business">using Claude in business</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">In practice</span>
    <h2 class="h2">A real before-and-after</h2>
    <p class="body">Picture the most common version of this task. You have just finished a 12-page quarterly review in Word. The analysis is right, but it is a patchwork: three different heading styles from three contributors, a table pasted from a spreadsheet that no longer fits the page, and no summary, because you ran out of time. Sending it as-is looks careless. Fixing it by hand is an hour you do not have.</p>
    <p class="body">Uploaded to Claude with a clear instruction, that same document comes back in a few minutes as one clean report: a one-page executive summary at the top, consistent headings throughout, the table reformatted and readable, and the prose tightened without changing a single fact. You spend ten minutes confirming the substance is intact and the numbers are right, then send it. The work you actually did, the analysis, is unchanged. The hour of reformatting is simply gone. Multiply that across every report, deck, and summary a team produces in a quarter and the saved time stops being a rounding error and starts being real capacity.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">Stay reliable</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Two things to watch for</h2>
    <p class="body"><strong>Verify the numbers and claims yourself.</strong> Claude preserves the data you give it and presents it cleanly, but you are the one accountable for whether a figure is correct. Treat its output like a sharp junior colleague's draft: trustworthy on structure, your responsibility on substance. A polished document with a wrong number is worse than a rough one with the right number, so the review step is not optional.</p>
    <p class="body"><strong>Give it your standard rather than hoping it guesses.</strong> If "polished" means something specific at your firm, a particular structure, a tone, a template, say so once and keep it in a Project. Left to guess, Claude produces something good but generic. Given your standard, it produces something that looks like your firm made it. The difference between those two outcomes is a few sentences of instruction, which is the cheapest investment in this entire workflow and the one most people skip.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <div class="sec-inner">
    <span class="lbl">FAQ</span>
    <h2 class="h2">Common questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-q">Can Claude actually produce a finished Word document?</div>
    <p class="body">Yes. Claude can produce properly formatted documents, including Word files with headings, a contents list, and a cover page, using its document Skills. You upload your rough material, describe the output, and download the finished file. You are reviewing and sending, not reformatting.</p>

    <div class="faq-q">Will it keep my numbers and tables accurate?</div>
    <p class="body">It preserves the data you give it, but always sanity-check the figures, as you would a junior colleague's draft. Claude is excellent at restructuring and presenting a table cleanly. You remain responsible for confirming the underlying numbers before anything goes out.</p>

    <div class="faq-q">Can it turn a report into slides?</div>
    <p class="body">Yes. Hand Claude a report and ask for a presentation outline or a deck, and it pulls the key points into a slide-ready structure, then builds the deck if you ask. You still apply judgment on emphasis and story, but the restructuring is done for you.</p>

    <div class="faq-q">Do I need special software or skills?</div>
    <p class="body">No. You work in the normal Claude app: upload a file, ask for the format you want, download the result. There is nothing technical involved and nothing to install. If you can attach a document to an email, you can do this.</p>

    <div class="faq-q">How is this different from copy and paste?</div>
    <p class="body">Copy and paste moves text. Claude restructures it: it rewrites for clarity, applies consistent formatting, builds summaries and tables, and outputs a finished file. The point is to skip the manual reformatting entirely, not just move words around.</p>
  </div>
</section>

